_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Route_20_in_Iowa"}
{"title_page": "George Speake", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = George Speake\n| honorific_suffix  = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}}\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| home_town         =\n| other_names       = \n| siglum            =\n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = [[England]]\n| fields            = [[Art history]] and archaeology\n| workplaces        = [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]] at Oxford\n| patrons           = \n| education         = [[Slade School of Fine Art]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Oxford]]\n| thesis_title      = Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = 1974\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = [[Christopher Hawkes]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Leading authority on [[Anglo-Saxon]] animal art\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''George Speake''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} is an English art historian and archaeologist.{{sfn|Barbican Research}}{{sfn|Speake CV}} He is an Honorary Research Fellow at the [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]] at [[Oxford]],{{sfn|Barbican Research}}{{sfn|Speake CV}} and \"a leading authority on Anglo-Saxon animal art.\"{{sfn|Barbican Research}} Currently Speake is the Anglo-Saxon Art and Iconography Specialist for the [[Staffordshire Hoard]] conservation team,{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=34, 41}} and is working on the reconstruction of the [[Staffordshire helmet]].{{sfn|ICON|2016}}{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}}\n\n==Early life and education==\nGeorge Speake was educated at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] in the 1960s, and the [[University of Oxford]], where he studied at [[St John's College, Oxford|St John's College]] and at the [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]], in the 1970s.{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}} At Oxford he studied under [[Christopher Hawkes|Christopher]] and [[Sonia Chadwick Hawkes|Sonia Hawkes]], obtaining a [[Ph.D.]] in 1974 with a thesis about [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] animal art.{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}}{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}}\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Staffordshire helmet terminal.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour photograph of the horse terminal from the Staffordshire helmet|Horse head terminal from the [[Staffordshire helmet]]]]\nSpeake specialises in Anglo-Saxon art and iconography.{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=29, 34, 41}} As of 2016 he is working on the reconstruction of the more than 1,000 pieces of the [[Staffordshire helmet]],{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=34, 41}}{{sfn|ICON|2016}} following work on the [[Royal Saxon tomb in Prittlewell|Prittlewell burial]], and teaching fine art and art history.{{sfn|Barbican Research}} In 2014 he coauthored a book on the [[Staffordshire Hoard]], ''Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard'', identifying among other characteristics an \"eyeless, open-jawed serpent\" depicted on the helmet's cheek guard.{{sfn|Fern|Speake|2014|p=34}} A paper on the helmet is due to be published in 2018.{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}} He is also an Honorary Research Fellow at the Institute of Archaeology at Oxford.{{sfn|Barbican Research}}\n\nSpeake's 1980 work ''Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background'',{{sfn|Speake|1980}} written as the basis for his Ph.D.,{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}} is considered \"a major break-through in Anglo-Saxon style studies\".{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=448}} It provided a comprehensive look at \"[[Migration Period art#Animal style|style II]]\" art,{{sfn|Hills|1981|p=225}} the form of zoomorphic decoration used in [[Northern Europe]] from the middle of the sixth century AD to the end of the seventh.{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}} Hitherto the least understood style of Anglo-Saxon and [[Scandinavia]]n animal art,{{sfn|Raw|1981|p=327}}{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}} style II is thought to have been reserved for the upper classes and is found prominently on the objects found in the [[Sutton Hoo]] [[ship burial|ship-burial]] and in the [[Vendel]] boat graves.{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=447}}{{sfn|Higgitt|1982|pp=62\u201363}} Speake's work was credited with discussing every known example of the style through 1974\u2014the date of his Ph.D.\u2014and with proving that it was introduced to England from [[Denmark]], [[Norway]], and [[Sweden]].{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|pp=446\u2013447}}\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 1970 | title = A Seventh-Century Coin Pendant from Bacton, Norfolk and its Ornament | journal = Medieval Archaeology | publisher = Society for Medieval Archaeology | series = | volume = 14 | issue = | pages = 1\u201316 | doi =  10.1080/00766097.1970.11735323| url = http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-769-1/dissemination/pdf/vol14/14_001_016.pdf }} {{open access}}\n* {{cite journal  | last1 = Hawkes | first1 = Sonia Chadwick | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | last3 = Northover | first3 = Peter | date = December 1979 | title = A Seventh-Century Bronze Metalworker\u2019s Die from Rochester, Kent | journal = Fr\u00fchmittelalterliche Studien | series = | volume = 13 | issue = | pages = 382\u2013392 | doi = 10.1515/9783110242126.382 | lastauthoramp = yes }} {{closed access}}\n* {{Cite book  | last = Speake | first = George | title = Anglo-Saxon Animal Art | date = 1980 | publisher = Clarendon Press | location = Oxford | isbn = 0-19-813194-1 }}\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 1982 | title = A Romano-British sculptured relief from Stonesfield, Oxon | journal = The Antiquaries Journal | publisher = Society of Antiquaries of London | series = | volume = LXII | issue = 2 | pages = 377\u2013379 | doi = 10.1017/S0003581500065975 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 1989 | title = A Saxon Bed-Burial on Swallowcliffe Down | journal = English Heritage Archaeological Reports | publisher = Historic Buildings and Monuments Commission for England | location = London | series = | volume = 10 | issue = | isbn = 1-85074-211-1 }}\n* {{Cite book  | last1 = Dickinson | first1 = Tania M. | author1-link = Tania Dickinson | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | editor-last = Carver | editor-first = Martin | editor-link = Martin Carver | title = The Age of Sutton Hoo: The seventh century in north-western Europe | date = 1992 | publisher = Boydell Press | location = Woodbridge | pages = 95\u2013130 | chapter = The Seventh-Century Cremation Burial in Asthall Barrow, Oxfordshire: A Reassessment | isbn = 0-85115-330-5 | lastauthoramp = yes }}\n* {{cite book  | last = Speake | first = George | editor1-last = Henig | editor1-first = Martin | editor2-last = Smith | editor2-first = Tyler Jo | date = 2007 | title = Collectanea Antiqua: Essays in Memory of Sonia Chadwick Hawkes | series = British Archaeological Reports | volume = 1673 | issue = | pages = 127\u2013131 | chapter = Interlace: Thoughts and Observations | isbn = 978-1407301082 | lastauthoramp = yes }}\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 2012 | title = An Early Romano-British Villa at Combe East End | journal = Oxoniensia | publisher = Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society | volume = LXXVII | issue = | pages = 1\u201390 | issn = 0308-5562 }}\n* {{ Cite book  | last1 = Fern | first1 = Chris | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | title = Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard | date = 2014 | publisher = West Midlands History | location = Warwickshire | isbn = 978-1-905036-20-2 }}\n* Speake, George. ''Aspects of the Staffordshire Hoard Helmet'' (forthcoming).{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last1 = Butterworth | first1 = Jenni | last2 = Fregni | first2 = Giovanna | last3 = Fuller | first3 = Kayleigh | last4 = Greaves | first4 = Pieta | date = 2016 | title = The importance of multidisciplinary work within archaeological conservation projects: assembly of the Staffordshire Hoard die-impressed sheets | journal = Journal of the Institute of Conservation | publisher = [[Institute of Conservation]] | volume = 39 | issue = 1 | pages = 29\u201343 | doi = 10.1080/19455224.2016.1155071 | lastauthoramp = yes }}\n* {{cite web | ref = {{harvid|Speake CV}} | last = | first = | title = George Speake DFA(Lond) DPhil FSA | date = | website = Barbican Research Associates | publisher = | url = http://www.barbicanra.co.uk/assets/george-speake--staff-hoard-cv.pdf | accessdate = 14 June 2017 }} {{open access}}\n* {{ Cite book  | last1 = Fern | first1 = Chris | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | title = Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard | date = 2014 | publisher = West Midlands History | location = Warwickshire | isbn = 978-1-905036-20-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Hawkes | first = Sonia Chadwick | author-link = Sonia Chadwick Hawkes | date = September 1983 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = The Antiquaries Journal | publisher = Society of Antiquaries of London | series = | volume = LXIII | issue = 3 | pages = 446\u2013448 | doi = 10.1017/S0003581500067019 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Higgitt | first = John | date = 1982 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = Journal of the British Archaeological Association  | publisher = | series = | volume = 135 | issue = 1 | pages = 62\u201364 | doi = 10.1179/jba.1982.135.1.62 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Hills | first = Catherine | date = November 1981 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = Antiquity | publisher = | series = | volume = LV | issue = 215 | pages = 225\u2013226 | doi = 10.1017/S0003598X00044288 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite web | ref = {{harvid|ICON|2016}} | last = | first = | title = A hoard act to follow: catching up with the Staffordshire conservation team | date = 8 February 2016 | website = [[Institute of Conservation]] | publisher = | url = https://icon.org.uk/news/revisiting-staffordshire-hoard | accessdate = 14 June 2017 }} {{open access}}\n* {{cite web | ref = {{harvid|Peopling Insular Art|2017}} | last = | first = | title = Peopling Insular Art: Practice, Performance, Perception | date = May 2017 | website = University of Glasgow | publisher = | url = http://www.gla.ac.uk/media/media_519256_en.pdf | accessdate = 14 June 2017 }} {{open access}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Raw | first = Barbara C. | date = 1981 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = Medium \u00c6vum | publisher = | series = | volume = L | issue = 1 | pages = 327\u2013328 | jstor = 43628628 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{Cite book  | last = Speake | first = George | title = Anglo-Saxon Animal Art | date = 1980 | publisher = Clarendon Press | location = Oxford | isbn = 0-19-813194-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web | ref = {{harvid|Barbican Research}} | last = | first = | title = The Typology and Art History Team | date = | website = Barbican Research Associates | publisher = | url = http://www.barbicanra.co.uk/typology.html | accessdate = 14 June 2017 }} {{open access}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Young | first = Bailey K. | date = 1983 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = Revue Arch\u00e9ologique | publisher = | series = | volume = | issue = 2 | pages = 375\u2013378 | jstor = 41737074 }} {{closed access}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speake, George}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English archaeologists]]\n[[Category:English art historians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxon studies scholars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = George Speake\n| honorific_suffix  = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}}\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| home_town         =\n| other_names       = \n| siglum            =\n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = [[England]]\n| fields            = [[Art history]] and archaeology\n| workplaces        = [[Institute of Archaeology]] at Oxford\n| patrons           = \n| education         = [[Slade School of Fine Art]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Oxford]]\n| thesis_title      = Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = 1974\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = [[Christopher Hawkes]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Leading authority on [[Anglo-Saxon]] animal art\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''George Speake''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} is an English art historian and archaeologist.{{sfn|Barbican Research}}{{sfn|Speake CV}} He is an Honorary Research Fellow at the [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]] at [[Oxford]],{{sfn|Barbican Research}}{{sfn|Speake CV}} and \"a leading authority on Anglo-Saxon animal art.\"{{sfn|Barbican Research}} Currently Speake is the Anglo-Saxon Art and Iconography Specialist for the [[Staffordshire Hoard]] conservation team,{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=34, 41}} and is working on the reconstruction of the [[Staffordshire helmet]].{{sfn|ICON|2016}}{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}}\n\n==Early life and education==\nGeorge Speake was educated at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] in the 1960s, and the [[University of Oxford]], where he studied at [[St John's College, Oxford|St John's College]] and at the [[Institute of Archaeology (Oxford)|Institute of Archaeology]], in the 1970s.{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}} At Oxford he studied under [[Christopher Hawkes|Christopher]] and [[Sonia Chadwick Hawkes|Sonia Hawkes]], obtaining a [[Ph.D.]] in 1974 with a thesis about [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] animal art.{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}}{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}}\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Staffordshire helmet terminal.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour photograph of the horse terminal from the Staffordshire helmet|Horse head terminal from the [[Staffordshire helmet]]]]\nSpeake specialises in Anglo-Saxon art and iconography.{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=29, 34, 41}} As of 2016 he is working on the reconstruction of the more than 1,000 pieces of the [[Staffordshire helmet]],{{sfn|Butterworth|Fregni|Fuller|Greaves|2016|pp=34, 41}}{{sfn|ICON|2016}} following work on the [[Royal Saxon tomb in Prittlewell|Prittlewell burial]], and teaching fine art and art history.{{sfn|Barbican Research}} In 2014 he coauthored a book on the [[Staffordshire Hoard]], ''Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard'', identifying among other characteristics an \"eyeless, open-jawed serpent\" depicted on the helmet's cheek guard.{{sfn|Fern|Speake|2014|p=34}} A paper on the helmet is due to be published in 2018.{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}} He is also an Honorary Research Fellow at the Institute of Archaeology at Oxford.{{sfn|Barbican Research}}\n\nSpeake's 1980 work ''Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background'',{{sfn|Speake|1980}} written as the basis for his Ph.D.,{{sfn|Speake|1980|p=vii}} is considered \"a major break-through in Anglo-Saxon style studies\".{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=448}} It provided a comprehensive look at \"[[Migration Period art#Animal style|style II]]\" art,{{sfn|Hills|1981|p=225}} the form of zoomorphic decoration used in [[Northern Europe]] from the middle of the sixth century AD to the end of the seventh.{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}} Hitherto the least understood style of Anglo-Saxon and [[Scandinavia]]n animal art,{{sfn|Raw|1981|p=327}}{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=446}} style II is thought to have been reserved for the upper classes and is found prominently on the objects found in the [[Sutton Hoo]] [[ship burial|ship-burial]] and in the [[Vendel]] boat graves.{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|p=447}}{{sfn|Higgitt|1982|pp=62\u201363}} Speake's work was credited with discussing every known example of the style through 1974\u2014the date of his Ph.D.\u2014and with proving that it was introduced to England from [[Denmark]], [[Norway]], and [[Sweden]].{{sfn|Hawkes|1983|pp=446\u2013447}}\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 1970 | title = A Seventh-Century Coin Pendant from Bacton, Norfolk and its Ornament | journal = Medieval Archaeology | publisher = Society for Medieval Archaeology | series = | volume = 14 | issue = | pages = 1\u201316 | doi =  10.1080/00766097.1970.11735323| url = http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-769-1/dissemination/pdf/vol14/14_001_016.pdf }} {{open access}}\n* {{cite journal  | last1 = Hawkes | first1 = Sonia Chadwick | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | last3 = Northover | first3 = Peter | date = December 1979 | title = A Seventh-Century Bronze Metalworker\u2019s Die from Rochester, Kent | journal = Fr\u00fchmittelalterliche Studien | series = | volume = 13 | issue = | pages = 382\u2013392 | doi = 10.1515/9783110242126.382 | lastauthoramp = yes }} {{closed access}}\n* {{Cite book  | last = Speake | first = George | title = Anglo-Saxon Animal Art | date = 1980 | publisher = Clarendon Press | location = Oxford | isbn = 0-19-813194-1 }}\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 1982 | title = A Romano-British sculptured relief from Stonesfield, Oxon | journal = The Antiquaries Journal | publisher = Society of Antiquaries of London | series = | volume = LXII | issue = 2 | pages = 377\u2013379 | doi = 10.1017/S0003581500065975 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 1989 | title = A Saxon Bed-Burial on Swallowcliffe Down | journal = English Heritage Archaeological Reports | publisher = Historic Buildings and Monuments Commission for England | location = London | series = | volume = 10 | issue = | isbn = 1-85074-211-1 }}\n* {{Cite book  | last1 = Dickinson | first1 = Tania M. | author1-link = Tania Dickinson | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | editor-last = Carver | editor-first = Martin | editor-link = Martin Carver | title = The Age of Sutton Hoo: The seventh century in north-western Europe | date = 1992 | publisher = Boydell Press | location = Woodbridge | pages = 95\u2013130 | chapter = The Seventh-Century Cremation Burial in Asthall Barrow, Oxfordshire: A Reassessment | isbn = 0-85115-330-5 | lastauthoramp = yes }}\n* {{cite book  | last = Speake | first = George | editor1-last = Henig | editor1-first = Martin | editor2-last = Smith | editor2-first = Tyler Jo | date = 2007 | title = Collectanea Antiqua: Essays in Memory of Sonia Chadwick Hawkes | series = British Archaeological Reports | volume = 1673 | issue = | pages = 127\u2013131 | chapter = Interlace: Thoughts and Observations | isbn = 978-1407301082 | lastauthoramp = yes }}\n* {{cite journal  | last = Speake | first = George | date = 2012 | title = An Early Romano-British Villa at Combe East End | journal = Oxoniensia | publisher = Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society | volume = LXXVII | issue = | pages = 1\u201390 | issn = 0308-5562 }}\n* {{ Cite book  | last1 = Fern | first1 = Chris | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | title = Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard | date = 2014 | publisher = West Midlands History | location = Warwickshire | isbn = 978-1-905036-20-2 }}\n* Speake, George. ''Aspects of the Staffordshire Hoard Helmet'' (forthcoming).{{sfn|Peopling Insular Art|2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last1 = Butterworth | first1 = Jenni | last2 = Fregni | first2 = Giovanna | last3 = Fuller | first3 = Kayleigh | last4 = Greaves | first4 = Pieta | date = 2016 | title = The importance of multidisciplinary work within archaeological conservation projects: assembly of the Staffordshire Hoard die-impressed sheets | journal = Journal of the Institute of Conservation | publisher = [[Institute of Conservation]] | volume = 39 | issue = 1 | pages = 29\u201343 | doi = 10.1080/19455224.2016.1155071 | lastauthoramp = yes }}\n* {{cite web | ref = {{harvid|Speake CV}} | last = | first = | title = George Speake DFA(Lond) DPhil FSA | date = | website = Barbican Research Associates | publisher = | url = http://www.barbicanra.co.uk/assets/george-speake--staff-hoard-cv.pdf | accessdate = 14 June 2017 }} {{open access}}\n* {{ Cite book  | last1 = Fern | first1 = Chris | last2 = Speake | first2 = George | title = Beasts, Birds and Gods: Interpreting the Staffordshire Hoard | date = 2014 | publisher = West Midlands History | location = Warwickshire | isbn = 978-1-905036-20-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Hawkes | first = Sonia Chadwick | author-link = Sonia Chadwick Hawkes | date = September 1983 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = The Antiquaries Journal | publisher = Society of Antiquaries of London | series = | volume = LXIII | issue = 3 | pages = 446\u2013448 | doi = 10.1017/S0003581500067019 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Higgitt | first = John | date = 1982 | title = Review: Anglo-Saxon Animal Art and its Germanic Background | journal = Journal of the British Archaeological Association  | publisher = | series = | volume = 135 | issue = 1 | pages = 62\u201364 | doi = 10.1179/jba.1982.135.1.62 }} {{closed access}}\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv | last = Hills | first = Catherine | date = November 1981 | title = Re