{"title_page": "Asghar Nadeem Syed", "text_new": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n'''Asghar Nadeem Syed''' (\u0627\u0635\u063a\u0631 \u0646\u062f\u06cc\u0645 \u0633\u06cc\u062f) (born 14 January 1950) is a Pakistani playwright, a TV drama serial writer as well as a poet.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/926953/literary-gathering-conference-on-sino-pak-literature-from-28th/ Literary gathering: Conference on China-Pakistan literature from 28th] The Express Tribune (newspaper), Published 27 July 2015. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>. he wrot many [[Dramas]] for Pakistani state channel ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) and other channels as like \"Chand Grahan\", which is most high rated drama of 90's and showned on [[Shalimar Television Network|STN]], and other Dramas [[1993]]'s hit \"[[Nijaat]]\" and [[1997]]'s \"Hawaien\", these two Classical Dramas were aired by ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]). 1998's another Classical ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) Drama \"Ghulam Gardish\" is also on his Credit, wich was directed by [[Nusrat Thakur]].\n\n\n==Early life and career==\nHe was born in 1950 in the city of [[Multan]]. He received his master's degree in Urdu language from the [[University of Punjab]], Lahore and then did his PhD degree from [[Bahauddin Zakariya University]], Multan.<ref name=Punjab/> He is married and has three children, a son and two daughters. Syed wrote the popular TV play ''Chaand Garahn'', an Urdu TV drama serial. At one time, Asghar Nadeem Syed was a media consultant at the [[Pakistan Television Corporation]].<ref name=Punjab/>\n\nHis dramas depict the social injustices in the society. He has written plays depicting the feudal culture in rural Sindh, exploitation of women, the oligarchic structure in Pakistan comprising politicians, feudals, media moguls and the bureaucracy.\n\nIn January 2014, he was wounded by some unknown assailants in a gun attack in [[Lahore]]. He was returning home from his job as head of the Department of Television, Film and Theatre at [[Beaconhouse National University]] in Lahore, when they shot at his car near [[Shaukat Khanum Hospital]].<ref>[http://tribune.com.pk/story/661464/playwright-asghar-nadeem-syed-attacked-near-shaukat-khanum-hospital/ Playwright Asghar Nadeem Syed survives gun attack in Lahore] The Express Tribune (newspaper), Published 21 January 2014. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1081750 Playwright Asghar Nadeem Syed injured in Lahore firing] Dawn (newspaper), Published 21 January 2014. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref> He has a total of 36 years of teaching experience.<ref name=Punjab/>\n\n==TV Plays==\n* Chand Grahan (\u0686\u0627\u0646\u062f \u06af\u0631\u06c1\u0646) (aired on Shalimar Television Network)\n* [[Nijaat]] (aired on [[PTV National|PTV]])\n* Hawaien (The Winds)  1997 ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) <ref>http://ptv1964-2000.blogspot.com/2016/</ref>\n* Ghulam Gardish  1998 ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SGRr89UO2I8</ref>\n* [[Riyasat]] (aired on [[Geo TV]]) [[2005]] <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3867586/</ref>\n* Bol Meri Machli (aired on [[Geo TV]])\n* Khuda Zameen Se Gaya Nahin (2009) (aired on [[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]])<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1442862/bio TV Plays by Asghar Nadeem Syed on IMDb website]. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>*\n\n==Literary activities==\nIn 2013, he served on the ''Board of Governors'' of [[Pakistan Academy of Letters]], an institution of Pakistani scholars and writers.<ref>[http://www.pal.gov.pk/?s=Asghar+Nadeem+Syed Asghar Nadeem Syed on Pakistan Academy of Letters website]. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* [[Pride of Performance]] Award by the [[President of Pakistan]] in 2006<ref>[http://fp.brecorder.com/2006/03/20060324402039/ Asghar Nadeem Syed's Pride of Performance Award info listed on Business Recorder (newspaper)] Published 24 March 2006. Retrieved 27 February 2018</ref><ref name=Punjab>[http://mpdd.punjab.gov.pk/system/files/Mr.%20Asghar%20Nadeem%20Syed.pdf Profile of Asghar Nadeem Syed on Punjab.gov.pk website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227153658/http://mpdd.punjab.gov.pk/system/files/Mr.%20Asghar%20Nadeem%20Syed.pdf |date=27 February 2018 }}. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>\n*[[Pakistan Television Corporation]] Award for Best Writer<ref name=Punjab/>\n\n==Books==\n* ''Aadhe Chand Ki Raat''<ref>[https://www.rekhta.org/Search/All?lang=1&q=Asghar%20Nadeem%20Syed Books written by Asghar Nadeem Syed on rekhta.org website]. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>\n* ''Tarz-e-Ehsas''\n* ''Adhoori Kulliyat''<ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1175295/questioning-society-and-identity-review-of-adhoori-kulliyat Questioning society and identity: Review of Adhoori Kulliyat] Dawn (newspaper), Published 12 April 2015. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1442862/bio Asghar Nadeem Syed on IMDb]\n\n{{Pride of Performance for Arts}}\n{{PTV Programs}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Syed, Asghar Nadeem}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:People from Multan]]\n[[Category:Pakistani dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Beaconhouse National University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pride of Performance]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n'''Asghar Nadeem Syed''' (\u0627\u0635\u063a\u0631 \u0646\u062f\u06cc\u0645 \u0633\u06cc\u062f) (born 14 January 1950) is a Pakistani playwright, a TV drama serial writer as well as a poet.<ref>[https://tribune.com.pk/story/926953/literary-gathering-conference-on-sino-pak-literature-from-28th/ Literary gathering: Conference on China-Pakistan literature from 28th] The Express Tribune (newspaper), Published 27 July 2015. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>. he wrot many [[Dramas]] for Pakistani state channel ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) and other channels as like \"Chand Grahan\", which is most high rated drama of 90's and showned on [[Shalimar Television Network|STN]], and other Dramas [[1993]]'s hit \"[[Nijaat]]\" and [[1997]]'s \"Hawaien\", these two Classical Dramas were aired by ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]). 1998's an other Classical ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) Drama \"Ghulam Gardish\" is also on his Credit, wich was directed by [[Nusrat Thakur]].\n\n\n==Early life and career==\nHe was born in 1950 in the city of [[Multan]]. He received his master's degree in Urdu language from the [[University of Punjab]], Lahore and then did his PhD degree from [[Bahauddin Zakariya University]], Multan.<ref name=Punjab/> He is married and has three children, a son and two daughters. Syed wrote the popular TV play ''Chaand Garahn'', an Urdu TV drama serial. At one time, Asghar Nadeem Syed was a media consultant at the [[Pakistan Television Corporation]].<ref name=Punjab/>\n\nHis dramas depict the social injustices in the society. He has written plays depicting the feudal culture in rural Sindh, exploitation of women, the oligarchic structure in Pakistan comprising politicians, feudals, media moguls and the bureaucracy.\n\nIn January 2014, he was wounded by some unknown assailants in a gun attack in [[Lahore]]. He was returning home from his job as head of the Department of Television, Film and Theatre at [[Beaconhouse National University]] in Lahore, when they shot at his car near [[Shaukat Khanum Hospital]].<ref>[http://tribune.com.pk/story/661464/playwright-asghar-nadeem-syed-attacked-near-shaukat-khanum-hospital/ Playwright Asghar Nadeem Syed survives gun attack in Lahore] The Express Tribune (newspaper), Published 21 January 2014. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.dawn.com/news/1081750 Playwright Asghar Nadeem Syed injured in Lahore firing] Dawn (newspaper), Published 21 January 2014. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref> He has a total of 36 years of teaching experience.<ref name=Punjab/>\n\n==TV Plays==\n* Chand Grahan (\u0686\u0627\u0646\u062f \u06af\u0631\u06c1\u0646) (aired on Shalimar Television Network)\n* [[Nijaat]] (aired on [[PTV National|PTV]])\n* Hawaien (The Winds)  1997 ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) <ref>http://ptv1964-2000.blogspot.com/2016/</ref>\n* Ghulam Gardish  1998 ([[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]]) <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SGRr89UO2I8</ref>\n* [[Riyasat]] (aired on [[Geo TV]]) [[2005]] <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3867586/</ref>\n* Bol Meri Machli (aired on [[Geo TV]])\n* Khuda Zameen Se Gaya Nahin (2009) (aired on [[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]])<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1442862/bio TV Plays by Asghar Nadeem Syed on IMDb website]. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>*\n\n==Literary activities==\nIn 2013, he served on the ''Board of Governors'' of [[Pakistan Academy of Letters]], an institution of Pakistani scholars and writers.<ref>[http://www.pal.gov.pk/?s=Asghar+Nadeem+Syed Asghar Nadeem Syed on Pakistan Academy of Letters website]. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n* [[Pride of Performance]] Award by the [[President of Pakistan]] in 2006<ref>[http://fp.brecorder.com/2006/03/20060324402039/ Asghar Nadeem Syed's Pride of Performance Award info listed on Business Recorder (newspaper)] Published 24 March 2006. Retrieved 27 February 2018</ref><ref name=Punjab>[http://mpdd.punjab.gov.pk/system/files/Mr.%20Asghar%20Nadeem%20Syed.pdf Profile of Asghar Nadeem Syed on Punjab.gov.pk website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227153658/http://mpdd.punjab.gov.pk/system/files/Mr.%20Asghar%20Nadeem%20Syed.pdf |date=27 February 2018 }}. Retrieved 26 February 2018</ref>\n*[[Pakistan Television Corporation]] Award for Best Writer<ref name=Punjab/>\n\